In late July 2006, bus benches in several Californian cities were decorated with promotional artwork for ''Christ Illusion''.<ref name="ExclusiveBenches">{{cite web
  | title =Exclusive: City Of Fullerton Demands That SLAYER Bus Benches Be Removed 
  | author =  
  | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]]
  | date = [[2006-08-01]]
  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=55902 
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> City officials in [[Fullerton, California]] demanded the artwork be immediately removed from seventeen bus benches located throughout the city, and contacted the hired company which had originally put the adverts in place to assume the task.<ref name="ExclusiveBenches"/> The officials disliked the band's name, which they felt referred to a murderer. They also took offense to the antichrist and skull logo adorning the bench artwork.<ref name="ExclusiveBenches"/> Eventually, the artwork was removed.<ref name="RemovedBenches">{{cite web
  | title = SLAYER 'Christ Illusion' Bus Benches Removed From Fullerton
  | author = 
  | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]]
  | date = [[2006-08-07]]
  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=56141
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> However, various Orange County, California areas surrounding the city of Fullerton still had benches sporting the cover artwork.<ref name="RemovedBenches"/>

==Critical reception==
''Christ Illusion'' was released on [[August 8]], [[2006]] by [[American Recordings]] / [[Warner Bros. Records]]. In its first week of release, the album sold 62,000 copies in the United States and debuted at number 5 on the [[Billboard 200]] Chart.<ref name="Billboard5">{{cite web| title = SLAYER: 'Christ Illusion' Lands At No. 5 On BILLBOARD Chart!|author=|publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|date=[[2006-08-16]]|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=56559
| accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> Though this ranked as the band's highest chart position to date, and was their first top 10 charting since [[1994 in music|1994]]'s ''[[Divine Intervention]]'',<ref name="Billboard5"/> the album dropped to number 44 the following week.<ref name="Metal, Rock and Alternative Music Doing Well In Billboard">{{cite web
  | title = Metal, Rock and Alternative Music Doing Well In Billboard
  | author =  | publisher = Metalunderground.com
  | date = [[2006-08-23]]  | url = http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=21264
  | accessdate = 2006-11-25 }}</ref> ''Christ Illusion'' reached number 9 in [[Australia]],<ref name="">{{cite web
  | title = SLAYER: 'Christ Illusion' Enters Australian Chart At No. 9
  | author =    | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]]  | date = [[2006-08-13]]
  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=56416
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> number 3 in [[Canada]], number 6 in [[Austria]], number 8 in the [[Netherlands]], number 10 in [[Norway]] and debuted at number 2 in [[Finland]]<ref name="SLAYER: 'Christ Illusion' Enters Finnish Chart At No. 2">{{cite web
  | title = SLAYER: 'Christ Illusion' Enters Finnish Chart At No. 2  | author =   | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]]
  | date = [[2006-08-13]]  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=56420
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> and [[Germany]].<ref name="ChartListings">{{cite web
  | title = SLAYER: 'Christ Illusion' Enters Norwegian Chart At No. 10  | author =  
  | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]]  | date = [[2006-08-16]]  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=56562
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> The single "[[Eyes of the Insane]]" won the "[[Best Metal Performance]]" category at the [[49th Grammy Awards]].<ref name="SLAYER Wins GRAMMY In 'Best Metal Performance' Category">{{cite web
  | title = 49th Annual Grammy Awards Winners List  | author =   | publisher = Grammy.com  | date = 
  | url = http://www.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/49th_Show/list.aspx  | accessdate = 2007-03-05 }}</ref> The song "Final Six" received a Grammy nomination at the [[50th Grammy Awards]].<ref name="Best Metal Performance ">{{cite web
|title=Best Metal Performance 
|publisher=Grammy.com
|url=http://www.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/50th_Show/list.aspx#04
|accessdate=2007-12-07}}</ref>

The album was met with generally favourable reviews. Thom Jurek of ''[[All Music Guide]]'' hailed the album as "raging, forward-thinking heavy metal melding with hardcore thrash", and wrote that ''Christ Illusion'' marked a return to "what made them such a breath of fresh air in the first place."<ref name="AllMusicReview">{{cite web| title = All Music Guide Review - ''Christ Illusion''|author = Jurek, Thom|publisher = [[All Music Guide]]|url = http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:rwf2zfi5eh7k~T1|accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> Ben Ratliff of the ''[[New York Times]]'' described the album as possessing "a kind of demented gravity, and the music bears it out: it is the most concentrated, focused Slayer record in 20 years."<ref name="NYTReview">{{cite news | last = Ratliff| first = Ben| title =New CD's| work =| pages =| publisher = New York Times  | date = 2006-08-14  | url =|accessdate=}}</ref> [[PopMatters]] critic Adrien Begrand called it "Slayer's best album in sixteen years and their most thought-provoking work to date",<ref name="PopMatters Review">{{cite web| title = PopMatters Review - ''Christ Illusion''|author = Begrand, Adrien|publisher = [[PopMatters]]|url = http://www.popmatters.com/pm/music/reviews/slayer-christ-illusion/|accessdate = 2007-03-16 }}</ref> and the album was placed at number 15 on [[PopMatters]] list of ''The Best Metal Albums of 2006''.<ref name="PopMatters Column">{{cite web| title = PopMatters Column - ''The Best Metal Albums of 2006''|author = Begrand, Adrien|publisher = [[PopMatters]]|url = http://www.popmatters.com/pm/columns/article/8836/the-best-metal-albums-of-2006/
|accessdate = 2007-03-16 }}</ref>
Drummer Lombardo came in for particular praise; though ''Rolling Stone'' slated the album, the reviewer acknowledged that "at least their awesome drummer Dave Lombardo shows off some chops."<ref name="StoneReview"/> ''[[Blabbermouth]]'''s Don Kaye thought that "while flawed", Christ Illusion "proves that the band still has a few tricks up its sleeve and one very potent weapon behind the kit."<ref name="BlabbermouthReview"/> Peter Atkinson of ''KNAC.com'' felt similarly, and reported Lombardo's "performance is top notch throughout and does give the album a looser feel than Paul Bostaph’s technical precision offered."<ref name="KNACReview"/>

Not all critics were so positive. Chris Steffen of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine dismissed the album, noting that it "mines much of the same territory as its predecessor, ''God Hates Us All'', just without the memorable riffs."<ref name="StoneReview">{{cite web
  | title = Advance of the Day: Slayer, “Christ Illusion”  | author = Steffen, Chris  | publisher = [[Rolling Stone]]
  | date = [[2006-07-07]]  | url = http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2006/07/07/advance-of-the-day-slayer-christ-illusion/ 
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> Jamie Thomson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' described the album as "wholly disappointing", and thought the band sounded "unwilling to ditch the nu-metal tendencies that have made much of their recent output so resistible."<ref name="GuardianReview"/> ''KNAC.com'' contributor Peter Atkinson felt that the album "demands OUTRAGE —more calculatingly so than any other album the band has done", "and that, in a nutshell, is ''Christ Illusion''’s glaring weakness."<ref name="KNACReview">{{cite web| title = KNAC Review - Christ Illusion  | author = Atkinson, Peter   | publisher = KNAC.com  | date = [[2006-07-24]]
  | url = http://www.knac.com/article.asp?ArticleID=4789  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref>

==Album artwork and lyrical themes==
Several aspects of ''Christ Illusion'''s content and promotion generated adverse attention and publicity. In particular the cover art, painted by [[Larry Carroll (artist)|Larry Carroll]] and depicting a mutilated, stoned Jesus, coupled with song lyrics which dealt with terrorism, warfare and religion, drew criticism  from conservative groups.

===Album artwork===
[[Image:Christ Illusion Alternate Cover.jpg|thumb|left|The censored album cover for ''Christ Illusion'', 2006]]
Carroll, who had painted the cover artwork to previous Slayer albums such as ''[[Reign in Blood]]'', ''[[South of Heaven]]'' and ''[[Seasons in the Abyss]]'', resumed duties on ''Christ Illusion''.<ref name="FinalArtwork">{{cite web
  | title = SLAYER: 'Christ Illusion' Final Album Artwork Posted Online
  | author =  
  | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]]
  | date = [[2006-06-15]] 
  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=53723
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> Working solely from track names and formative lyrics, Carroll produced the original on a 4-by-4-foot slab of wood using a combination of mediums.<ref name="FinalArtwork"/> Having requested an image of Christ in "a sea of despair", King commented that an early version seemed as though Christ was "chilling out in the water".<ref name="UnderFire">{{cite web
  | title = SLAYER Under Fire From Christian Groups
  | author = 
  | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]]
  | date = [[2006-06-05]]
  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=54652
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> The final image portrays Christ with a missing eye and amputated hands, and standing amidst a sea of blood and severed heads.<ref name="FinalArtwork"/> Araya deemed this version "much better because he looked like a drug addict!",<ref name="UnderFire"/> while King admired the artwork enough to purchase the original.<ref name="Kerry King: Interview">{{cite web
  | title = Kerry King: Interview
  | author = Horaczek, Stan 
  | publisher = Blender.com 
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?id=2011&src=jk08
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> Certain album pre-orders gave fans the chance to win one of ten autographed [[lithograph]]s of the artwork,<ref name="SLAYER: Win 'Christ Illusion' Album Cover Signed By Artist">{{cite web
  | title = SLAYER: Win 'Christ Illusion' Album Cover Signed By Artist
  | author =  
  | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]]
  | date = [[2006-07-27]]
  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=55704 
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> while an alternative, non-graphic cover was made to appease retailers who had refused to stock the original version.<ref name="SLAYER: 'Christ Illusion' Alternate 'Non-Graphic' Cover Revealed">{{cite web
  | title = SLAYER: 'Christ Illusion' Alternate 'Non-Graphic' Cover Revealed
  | author = 
  | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]]
  | date = [[2006-07-20]]
  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=55362
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref>

''World Entertainment News Network'' reported Slayer were attracting controversy through issuing the artwork.<ref name="UnderFire"/> Joseph Dias of the Mumbai Christian group ''Catholic Secular Forum'' took "strong exception" to the original album artwork, and issued a memorandum to Mumbai's police commissioner in protest.<ref name="IllusionRecalled">{{cite web
  | title = SLAYER's 'Christ Illusion' Album Recalled Following Christian Group Protests
  | author =  
  | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]]
  | date = [[2006-10-06]]
  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=59883
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> Chris Steffen of ''Rolling Stone'' magazine commented that "The album art takes it all over the top with an image axeman Kerry King dubs 'Christ in a Sea of Despair'",<ref name="StoneReview"/> while ''KNAC.com'''s Peter Atkinson deemed the artwork "defiantly sacrilegious".<ref name="KNACReview"/>

===Lyrical themes===
Lyrical themes explored on ''Christ Illusion'' include a depiction of the [[September 11, 2001 attacks|September 11 attacks]] from the viewpoint of one of the terrorists ("[[Jihad (song)|Jihad]]"),<ref name="SunInterview">{{cite web
  | title = It's carry on thrashing'
  | author =  
  | publisher = The Sun Online
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.thesun.co.uk/article/0,,2006380348,00-2006370167,00.html
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> and a portrayal of a soldier's experience of post-traumatic stress ("[[Eyes of the Insane]]").<ref name="Claes">{{cite web
  | title = Slayer
  | author = Claes, Sean
  | publisher = Blistering.com
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.blistering.com/fastpage/fpengine.php/link/1/templateid/12020/tempidx/5/menuid/3
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> The song "Cult" revolves around King's perception of flaws in American religion,<ref name="Metal gods Slayer gear up for this summer's most brutal road trek, the Unholy Alliance Tour">{{cite web
  | title = Metal gods Slayer gear up for this summer's most brutal road trek, the Unholy Alliance Tour
  | author = Sculley, Alan
  | publisher = CityBeat.com
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.citybeat.com/2006-06-14/music.shtml
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> while "Consfearacy" has been described as a "government hating song".<ref name="Piccoli1">{{cite web
  | title = Grammy for Slayer's 11th album shows metal legends are now a household name
  | author = Piccoli, Sean
  | publisher = Sun-Sentinel.com
  | date = 2007-02-21
  | url = http://www.sun-sentinel.com/features/lifestyle/sfl-mu21slayerfeb21,0,6340152.story?coll=sfla-features-headlines
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref><ref name="StatesmanJournal">{{cite web
  | title = SLAYER Guitarist KERRY KING: 'We Won't Change. We'll Always Be Angry
  | author =  
  | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]]
  | date = [[2006-06-13]]
  | url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=55010
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref>

{{Sound sample box align right|Music sample:}}
{{listen|
|filename=Slayer_Eyes_of_the_Insane_clip.ogg
|title="Eyes of the Insane"
|description=The Araya penned lyrics of "Eyes of the Insane" were inspired by an article called "Casualties of War" in Texas Monthly, dealing with the plight of soldiers suffering from [[post-traumatic stress]].<ref name="Claes"/>
||format=[[Ogg]]}}
{{sample box end}}
Critical reaction to the album's lyrical content was mixed. Thom Jurek of ''[[All Music Guide]]'' felt the "dark, unrelentingly twisted-as-fuck lyrics reflect a singular intensity", and praised the band for connecting their anti-religion stance with a belief that religion has underscored many wars throughout history.<ref name="AllMusicReview"/> However, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'''s Chris Steffen mourned that it had become "downright painful to hear Tom Araya — at 45 years old! — continue to belt out the band's increasingly self-parodying, anti-religious lyrics", and singled out lyrics such as "Religion's a whore" and "I've made my choice: six six six!" as over the top.<ref name="StoneReview"/> Jamie Thomson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that the album left "no blasphemy...unuttered",<ref name="GuardianReview"/> while Peter Atkinson of ''KNAC.com'' observed that "when not fixating on religion, the band revisit their other favorite subject — war — in surprisingly familiar terms", and remarked that Slayer had sunk "to the level of God-repelling dunderheads [[Deicide (band)|Deicide]]."<ref name="KNACReview"/> He concluded the review with the opinion that "It's déjà vu all over again from ''[[God Hates Us All]]'' — and once you've titled something ''God Hates Us All'', haven't you made your point enough already?"<ref name="KNACReview"/>

A Christian group, the [[Mumbai]] based ''Catholic Secular Forum'' (''CSF''), condemned the album's lyrical content. The organisation's general secretary Joseph Dias issued a statement in which he deemed the lyrics to "Skeleton Christ" to be an "insult to Christianity".<ref name="IllusionRecalled"/> The memorandum was sent to Mumbai's police commissioner, and further expressed concern that the track "[[Jihad (song)|Jihad]]" would offend "the sensibilities of the Muslims...and secular Indians who have respect for all faiths."<ref name="IllusionRecalled"/> EMI India met with the ''CSF'', apologising for ''Christ Illusion'''s release and recalling the album with no plans of a reissue.<ref name="IllusionRecalled"/> On [[October 11]], [[2006]] it was announced all stocks had been destroyed.<ref name="Offensive' album pulled in India">{{cite web
  | title = 'Offensive' album pulled in India
  | author =  
  | publisher = [[BBC.co.uk]]
  | date = [[2006-10-11]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6039976.stm 
  | accessdate = 2007-02-22 }}</ref> Though Araya had expected "Jihad"'s treatment of the events of 9/11 to create an American backlash,<ref name="SunInterview"/> it failed to materialise, in part, he believes, due to peoples' view that the song is merely "just Slayer being Slayer".<ref name="Luxi"/>

